85 Sì come neve tra le vive travi 86 per lo dosso d’Italia si congela, 87 soffiata e stretta da li venti schiavi,
88 poi, liquefatta, in sé stessa trapela, 89 pur che la terra che perde ombra spiri, 90 sì che par foco fonder la candela;
91 così fui sanza lagrime e sospiri 92 anzi ’l cantar di quei che notan sempre 93 dietro a le note de li etterni giri;
94 ma poi che ’ntesi ne le dolci tempre 95 lor compatire a me, par che se detto 96 avesser: ‘Donna, perché sì lo stempre?’,
97 lo gel che m’era intorno al cor ristretto, 98 spirito e acqua fessi, e con angoscia 99 de la bocca e de li occhi uscì del petto.

query.result:
85 So like snow among the lively beams 86 through the ridge of Italy it freezes, 87 blown and tightened by the slave winds,
88 then, liquefied, in itself it seeps, 89 even though the earth that loses shadow breathes, 90 so that it seems fire to melt the candle;
91 thus I was without tears and sighs 92 instead the singing of those who always note 93 behind the notes of the eternal circles;
94 but then that I understood in the sweet times 95 their compassion to me, seems that they said 96 to have: ‘Lady, why so they stare?’,
97 the frost that was around my narrowed heart, 98 spirit and water weary, and with anguish 99 from the mouth and from the eyes exited of the chest.

100 She, still firm on the said thigh 101 of the carriage standing, to the low substances foot 102 turned her words thus afterwards:
103 “You watch in the eternal day, 104 so that night nor sleep to you does not steal 105 step that the age makes for its ways;
106 wherefore my answer is with more care 107 that may understand me he who from there weeps, 108 because it may be fault and grief of a measure.”

